The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Melbourne, June 6 (PTI): The South Australia government will set up a forum to address security issues of Indian cab drivers following attacks on them that sparked protests by the community.          
	The decision came after representatives of the 1,000-strong community met the Indian consul-general in Sydney, Sujan Chinoy, and South Australia multicultural and ethnic affairs chairman Hieu van Le in Adelaide.                  
	Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): A bride refused to get married after the groom arrived at the wedding ceremony drunk. Suchitra, 26, was to marry Ramachandran on Thursday, but her refusal earned her appreciation from her relatives. Police intervened to prevent a confrontation between the two families.                   
	Kanpur (PTI): The Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur, will take help from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, US, to tackle student suicides, which have increased in the past three years. Psychologists and mental health experts from MIT will counsel IIT authorities on managing depression among students under severe academic stress.                  
	Coimbatore (PTI): Workers of the Hindu Makkal Katchi, a political party founded in the mid-90s, staged a demonstration on Friday, protesting Malaysias issuance of a trademark on ponni rice, which originated and is largely produced in Tamil Nadu. About 25 activists demanded the Centre take steps to protect the rights of Indian farmers, especially those in Tamil Nadu.                  
	Bangalore (PTI): Indias light combat aircraft Tejas has passed hot weather test flights in Nagpur, the air force has said.                   
	 Rajkot (PTI): A family of four, allegedly infected with HIV, committed suicide in Gujarat, police said on Friday. Mansukh Baldhar, his wife and their two children took poison when Mansukh came to know the disease was incurable.
                                                                                                                         
